- Helper: true / false (10% chance, shows operation name for 2 value commands)

Keyboard Shortcuts:
Clear: Delete, Space. Delete: Backspace.
0-9: 0-9, Numpad 0-9. Decimal: Period. Numpad Decimal.
Add: Shift+=, Numpad +. Subtract: -, Numpad -.
Multiply: Shift+8, Numpad -. Divide: /, Numpad /.
Equals: =, Enter, Numpad Enter, Numpad =.
Cut: Ctrl+X. Copy: Ctrl+C. Paste: Ctrl+V.
Negate: Shift+\, Shift+-. Modulo: Shift+5.
Power: Shift+6. Square Root: Q. Y Root X: R. Random: Shift+R. 1 / X: D.
E: E. Logarithm Y X : L. PI: P. Factorial: Shift+1, F.
Sin: S. Cos: C. Tan: T. Arc Toggle: A. Hyperbolic Toggle: H.
Floor: [. Round: \. Ceil: ].

metadata.name: Ode to Bugs and Happy Accidents #68
metadata.description:
‚ÄúIf debugging is the process of removing software bugs, then programming must be the process of putting them in.‚Äù

‚Äï¬†Edsger W. Dijkstra


This artwork is dedicated to happy accidents, mistakes, and bugs. Every key part of it is based on some sort of failure: wrong variable value, unstopped recursion, untimely function call. And sometimes it leads to pleasant results.

It was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- Processing Foundation
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine

[a] - toggle animation
[1] - save PNG in low resolution
[2] - save PNG in medium resolution
[3] - save PNG in high resolution
[4] - save PNG in ultra-high resolution

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js

By Collapsar Beauty
CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Para Metric #128
metadata.description: This collection of NFTs is based on an elementary mathematical principle; a parametric equation. Despite the simplicity of the principle, the results are simply stunning. All kinds of intricate shapes and patterns are formed by drawing random dots a parametric equation solely based on sines and cosines. Combined with a simple bright shape in the background, the art pieces are created. Every piece is highly unique can with different backgrounds and amount of shapes. I hope you enjoy the pieces!

metadata.name: Tangentum #180
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js

[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Speed of Dark #415
metadata.description:
Simple shapes, when strewn broadly and systematically, suggest the presence of infinite creative possibilities and are capable of portraying a visceral excitement felt by mixing the energy of light with the contemplation of dark.

This exercise has been repeated for ages, and its relevance will remain for as long as light may meet dark. The silhouettes of Stonehenge battling against a bright sky, the wabi-sabi placement of rocks in a Japanese garden hugged by methodical raking, the play of shadows in Plato's Allegory of the Cave, and the playfully arranged cut-outs of collage or chemical photogram ‚Äî these all attest to the unending dynamism of form when imbued with light and the contrast of its absence.

As absence and darkness are made visible, the trail of their path conveys a speed as fast as light, and dark shapes that are no less important than the brightest figures. A symbiotic coexistence of these forces was born with the universe ‚Äì and a delicate balance remains between the powerful glare of light and the stealthy speed of dark.

Inspired by photograms and a little-known series by documentary photographer William Klein, Speed of Dark references the visual language of the darkroom and the history of photography as an underlying analog for how an emerging art medium can harness simple elements to create evocative expressions.

Choose a resolution by adding "&width=9000" to the URL in live view.
Remove the border by adding "&noborder=1" to the URL.

__________
TENDER x Laurent Houdard
May 2022

metadata.name: Gribouillis #5
metadata.description:
"Gribouillis" tends to reproduce the result of what you could draw without too much thinking on your sketchbook; an automatic drawing while listening to a call or podcast... Or something you would draw on the napkin of a restaurant without a strong focus...
Those kind of drawing that don't have a lot of meaning, but that, sometimes, give you find some comfort.

---

This is a "screenshot" of the current researches and work I'm doing to emulate a sensation of sketching.

---

Open the link and add '#hd' in the URL to have a A3 size of the artwork.

---

Made to run in browser, especially Chrome.
Works on most recent iPhones.

---

Twitter: @florianzumbrunn
Instagram: @florianzumbrunn

metadata.name: cellular_collage #38
metadata.description:
Each token is a unique collage of two distinct Multi-Neighborhood Cellular Automata systems.

Click and drag to place noise on the canvas. Press the space bar to pause the simulation, and again to resume it. While paused, you can press "n" to advance the simulation by a single step.
